<section class="faq-hero"><p class="eyebrow">FAQs</p><h1>Before you begin.</h1><p>Short answers to common questions about diabetes reversal, medication safety, consultation and program readiness.</p></section><section class="faq-grid"><article><h2>Can Type 2 diabetes really go into remission?</h2><p>For many people, yes. Research shows remission is possible when weight, insulin resistance and the metabolic environment improve deeply enough. It is not guaranteed for everyone.</p></article><article><h2>Do you promise a cure?</h2><p>No. We do not make casual cure promises. We work seriously toward measurable metabolic improvement and remission where possible.</p></article><article><h2>Can I stop my medicines after joining?</h2><p>No one should stop diabetes medicines or insulin suddenly. If sugar improves, medicine changes must be handled with qualified medical supervision.</p></article><article><h2>What makes this different from general diet advice?</h2><p>The work is structured and therapeutic. It includes food rhythm, movement, sleep, stress, digestion, education, tracking and accountability, not vague advice to eat healthy.</p></article><article><h2>Who is this for?</h2><p>People with Type 2 diabetes, prediabetes, insulin resistance, excess weight, sugar instability or stress-linked eating patterns may benefit from a consultation.</p></article><article><h2>What should I bring to consultation?</h2><p>Recent HbA1c, fasting sugar, post-meal sugar, medicines, weight history, food routine, sleep pattern and any doctor advice you already follow.</p></article></section><section class="text-card compact"><h2>Still unsure?</h2><p>Start with a consultation. We will help you understand whether the program, store tools or another step is appropriate.</p><a class="pill ghost" href="<?php echo esc_url(home_url('/consultation/')); ?>">Book Consultation</a></section>
